./.title: Preface
./.body:
Tuya Security iOS SDK
Welcome to start your Tuya Security SDK access journey.

Overview.html.title: Features Overview
Overview.html.body:
Functional Overview
Tuya Security SDK is a set of iOS 9.0 and above SDK provided by Tuya Security for the home and business security field. iOS developers can quickly implement APP function development based on the SDK, and realize the functions of arming, disarming and security scenarios. The Tuya Security SDK is based on the Tuya Home SDK, which makes the upper-level security application scenarios, and integrates the Tuya IPC SDK to provide a wealth of camera capabilities.
Security SDK mainly includes the following

Security user service (Uid login, bound service code)
Arm and disarm (arm, disarm, alarm, cancel alarm, arm setting)
Security scenes (linkage scenes, geo-fencing, arming reminders, event binding)
Security messages (security arm and disarm messages, equipment messages)

Preparation.html.title: Preparation for Integration
Preparation.html.body:
1.1. Preparation
1.1.1 Registering a developer account
Go Tuya Development Platform registered developer account, create products, create points function, etc. please refer to the specific process Access Procedure
1.1.2 Create SDK Application
Click "App SDK" in "App Workbench" in Tuya IoT platform, and click to get SDK.

Choose a suitable development plan according to your needs and click "Next".
Note: For the security SDK, the IPC scheme needs to be checked here so that the SDK can provide Camera-related capabilities.

Can be obtained in the iOS section AppKey、AppSecret，click on the "Download security image", the security picture Rename t_s.bmp.

Note: For security, do not download the iOS (Podfile), use the version we provide. The specific focus is on the integration of Security SDK.

Integrated.html.title: Integrate SDK
Integrated.html.body:
1.1. Integrate Security SDK
1.1.1 Use CocoaPods to quickly integrate (the minimum SDK supports system version 9.0)
In the Podfile Add the following files:
platform :ios, '9.0'

target 'Your_Project_Name' do
  // Tuya Basical SDK
    pod 'TuyaSmartHomeKit','~>3.17.0'
  // Tuya Camera SDK
  pod 'TuyaSmartCameraKit', '~>4.17.1'
  pod 'TuyaSmartCameraT', '~>4.17.6'
  // Tuua Security SDK
  pod 'TuyaSmartSecurityBaseKit'
  pod 'TuyaSmartSecurityBizAopKit'
  pod 'TuyaSmartSecurityServiceKit'

end

And then execute the project root directory pod update command integrate.
For the use of CocoaPods, please refer to:CocoaPods GuidesCocoaPods is recommended to update to the latest version
1.1.2 Initialize SDK

Open the project settings, Target => General, modifyBundle Identifierit to the iOS package name corresponding to the App registered on the Tuya developer platform.

Import the security image downloaded in the abovePreparations into the project root directory, rename it tot_s.bmp and add it to "Project Settings => Target => Build Phases => Copy Bundle Resources".

PrefixHeader.pchAdd the following content to the project file (Swift project can be added in thexxx_Bridging-Header.hbridge file):
#import 
#import 
#import 
#import 
#import 


Open the AppDelegate.mfile, in the[AppDelegate application:didFinishLaunchingWithOptions:]method, used on graffiti developer platform, App corresponding App Key，App Secret initialize the SDK:
Objc
[[TuyaSmartSDK sharedInstance] startWithAppKey: secretKey:];



​      Swift:
TuyaSmartSDK.sharedInstance()?.start(withAppKey: , secretKey: )

At this point, Tuya Security App SDK has been successfully activated, and App development can begin.

iOSAdaptation.html.title: iOS Version Adaptation
iOSAdaptation.html.body:
During the development process, you can turn on the Debug mode and print some logs for problem analysis.
iOS 13 adaptation
Wi-Fi permission changes
Starting from iOS 13, if the geographic location permission is not turned on, [[TuyaSmartActivator sharedInstance] currentWifiSSID]the correct SSID will not be obtained (provided that the Wi-Fi permission is turned on). In this case, the system will return to WLAN or Wi-Fi by default. The following is Apple Official email description
As we announced at WWDC19, we're making changes to further protect user privacy and prevent unauthorized location tracking. Starting with iOS 13, the CNCopyCurrentNetworkInfo API will no longer return valid Wi-Fi SSID and BSSID information. Instead, the information returned by default will be: 

SSID: “Wi-Fi” or “WLAN” (“WLAN" will be returned for the China SKU)
BSSID: "00:00:00:00:00:00"

Confirm that the app has enabled geographic location permissions
Confirm that the BSSID obtained through the system method is 00:00:00:00:00:00, it is considered to be the default return of the system. The result is not available and requires additional processing by the developer, such as manually entering the Wi-Fi name.

Bluetooth permission changes
If you use the SDK to develop an integrated Tuya Bluetooth device, you must pay attention to the new "App Bluetooth permission" added in iOS 13. In the iOS 13 system, in addition to the system Bluetooth permission, each App will have its own Bluetooth permission. If Bluetooth is used in the app, each app will ask whether to allow the app to use Bluetooth permission before launching for the first time.
In iOS 13, the original Apple Bluetooth application for permission to use the NSBluetoothPeripheralUsageDescription field, replaced by NSBluetoothAlwaysUsageDescription fields. Add new fields in info.plist.

If you are compiling and using SDK to develop mesh functions in Xcode 11, the device may not be searched. You need to TuyaSmartBLEMeshKitupgrade to 2.12.47 or later, this version has been made fit; if other Xcode version, no update
When the user chooses not to allow it, it will affect the use of the Bluetooth function. At this time, it is recommended to guide the user to turn on the Bluetooth permission (the status of the Bluetooth center at this time is CBCentralManagerStateUnauthorized )

iOS 12 adaptation
iOS 12 use [[TuyaSmartActivator sharedInstance] currentWifiSSID] can not get to SSID
To obtain WiFi information in Xcode 10, you need to enable relevant permissions. The solution:

Xcode -> [Project Name] -> Targets -> [Target Name] -> Capabilities -> Access WiFi Information -> ON

Just open the above permissions.
